Networking basics in Linux Concepts learned: Introduction to TCP and UDP protocols, IP addresses, ports and their numbers, and connections like SSH, RDP and DNS. Commands: ip a — shows all network interfaces and their IPs, including the private IP and loopback. ping -c 4 [IP or web] — tests connectivity to an IP or website. The -c 4 sends only 4 packets and stops. ss -tulpn — audits open ports on the system: -t → TCP protocol processes -u → UDP protocol processes -l → ports that are listening for connections -p → process that opened the port -n → shows port numbers and IPs instead of names curl [web] — shows the content of a webpage. curl -I [web] shows only the HTTP headers, which tell us how the server protects users from web attacks. SSH: SSH is the secure remote access protocol. It must be monitored carefully because if an attacker obtains valid credentials, they can install software, steal data, and run processes on the system. Exercise — SSH logs in real time: Open two terminals. In the first run sudo tail -f /var/log/auth.log to monitor all authentication events in real time. In the second run ssh kali@[your IP]. The first terminal will show the login attempt and result. Use grep to filter SSH-specific events. Security headers (curl -I): Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS) — rejects unencrypted HTTP connections, forces HTTPS. Content-Security-Policy (CSP) — prevents browsers from loading scripts or resources from unknown domains.
